    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>

<p>In this exercise you will use Laplace expansion along the 1st row to determine the determinant of the following matrix:</p><div>\(A={@matrixa@}\)</div>

<p>Let the entries in the first row be denoted \(a_{1,1}\), \(a_{1,2}\) and \(a_{1,3}\) in the usual way. First list the cofactors \(A_{i,j}\) of these entries:</p>
<p>\(A_{1,1}=\)[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p>
<p>\(A_{1,2}=\)[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]</p>
<p>\(A_{1,3}=\)[[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]</p>

<p>Use these values to evaluate the determinant of \(A\): [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]</p>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[To obtain the cofactor of an element of a \(3 \times 3\) matrix we multiply the minor of that element by the corresponding sign from the \(3 \times 3\) array of signs.

For \(a_{1,1}\), the sign is \(+\), and the minor is \(\det{@matrix([AA[2,2], AA[2,3]], [AA[3,2], AA[3,3]])@}\). Hence the cofactor is \({@ta1@}.\)

For \(a_{1,2}\), the sign is \(-\), and the minor is \(\det{@matrix([AA[2,1], AA[2,3]], [AA[3,1], AA[3,3]])@}\). Hence the cofactor is \({@ta2@}.\)

For \(a_{1,3}\), the sign is \(+\) again, and the minor is \(\det{@matrix([AA[2,1], AA[2,2]], [AA[3,1], AA[3,2]])@}\). Hence the cofactor is \({@ta3@}.\)

The determinant of \(A\) is now given by the formula:
\[\det(A) = {@CC@} = {@DD@}\]]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
